<p style="text-align: center;"><span style="text-decoration: underline;"><strong>School Calendar Information</strong></span></p>
<p>We’re considering making adjustments to this year’s school calendar and next year's 2020-21 calendar. We’d like to inform you of our thinking about this.</p>
<p><strong>First, when will THIS YEAR end (2019-2020)?</strong></p>
<ul>
<li>In order to lengthen the summer construction schedule, we’re considering ending the school year for students and staff on <strong>Friday, May 22</strong> (the same day as senior graduation). We did something like this last year (2018-19), before a record setting winter arrived.</li>
<li>For students, this year is scheduled to end on <strong>Thursday, May 28</strong>. </li>
<li>We plan to make the decision on when to end the 2019-20 school year at the <strong>April 20</strong> School Board meeting, after the winter season is nearly finished.   </li>
</ul>
<p><strong>Second, when will NEXT YEAR start (2020-2021)?</strong></p>
<ul>
<li>Right now, we are scheduled to start the 2020-21 school year on <strong>Tuesday,</strong><strong>September 8</strong> (the day after the Labor Day holiday).  We’d like to keep it that way.</li>
<li>If the construction schedule is delayed, we’ll start the 2020-21 school year later than originally planned.  The question is: Should we adjust the calendar now? Or, wait until the summer projects are in full swing before deciding whether to delay the 2020-21 start date?  </li>
<li>Rather than make the decision now, we’ve decided to wait until <strong>July 20 </strong>School Board meeting before changing the start date.  </li>
</ul>
<p>We’ve sought feedback from the several groups (custodial, office staff, kitchen, daycare, transportation, athletic, principals, etc.) and this seems to be a sensible approach.</p>
